{
  "text": " Hello and welcome to this lecture in the series Introductions to Digital Humanities. Today I will talk about natural language processing. Let me first say a few words about myself. My name is Riko Sennig. I'm at the University of Zurich and my main area of research is natural language processing. During my PhD I worked mainly on machine translation, but I did that on historical text. That's also one link of mine to digital humanities. I worked on making the algorithms for machine translation of data preparation more robust for historical text, which were also noisy due to the digitization process. I spent 90 years at the University of Edinburgh, a bit more virtually, continuing working on machine translation. I have this illustration here for my work there showing that I focused on working on language representations, for example, some technical representations, but also virtual representations.",
